<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 93 / International Company News: Salomon debt downgraded by
Standard &amp; Poor's
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SALOMON, the US securities house, has had about Dollars 8bn of outstanding
debt downgraded by Standard &amp; Poor's, the US credit rating agency. The
downgrade, which could push up the cost of Salomon's borrowings, reflected
the firm's reliance on proprietary trading activity 'which has increased its
vulnerability to quarterly earnings volatility,' S&amp;P said.
Salomon's longer-term senior debt rating was cut to single A minus from
single A. Its subordinated debt rating fell to triple B plus from single A
minus. Preferred stock received a rating of triple B from triple B plus, and
the commercial paper rating was cut to A-2 from A-1.
Mr Donald Howard, chief financial officer said: 'Some rating agencies focus
too heavily on the short-term volatility of Salomon's earnings and give
inadequate weight to our results measured over longer time-frames and to the
exceptional quality and liquidity of our assets.'
</TEXT>
