<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 93 / International Company News: Credit Lyonnais to lift BFH
stake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CREDIT Lyonnais, the French state-controlled banking group, is to increase
its holding in Banque Franco-Hellenique de Commerce International et
Maritime (BFH), an Athens-based bank, to 75 per cent by acquiring a 25 per
cent stake.
The French bank has agreed to buy the 25 per cent of BFH from the
state-owned National Investment Bank for Industrial Development (Eteva) for
an undisclosed sum. Eteva will retain the remaining 25 per cent.
Under the terms of the agreement, BFH, with a net worth of about Dr7bn
(Dollars 32m), will be expected to seek a listing on the Athens stock
exchange within the next three years.
Credit Lyonnais has managed BFH since it was set up 12 years ago when Greece
joined the European Community. In addition to trade financing, BFH has built
up a shipping portfolio and is expanding into private banking.
Eteva, an investment bank controlled by National Bank of Greece, the
country's largest state-owned bank, has been trying to dispose of its
holding in BHF for some time.
Eteva plans to move into commercial banking, building a network of branches
around Greece, as its development role has been curtailed by the
government's privatisation policy.
</TEXT>
