<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There will, I imagine, be cheering as today's Dispatches goes out (9.00 C4).
It reports on small businessmen who live in fear of the Inland Revenue and
recounts stories of intimidation by tax inspectors. One former tax man
asserts 'Most inspectors believe that all small traders are fiddling'. There
are horrific tales of a couple who had to pay their life savings to the
Revenue, and of a publican who died after being pursued by inspectors over
profits he could never have made. Tomorrow's World screens a report from
Paris featuring rental schemes for electric cars, a system for superimposing
different adverts on billboards, and computerisation of the organ in Notre
Dame (7.30 BBC1). QED seeks to show what will be the effects of the next
Tokyo earthquake; the last was 70 years ago and the next is now due. This
time, owing to Tokyo's key position in the world economy, the effects may be
international (9.35 BBC1). BBC2 begins a six-part series which has been
causing difficulties before even reaching the screen: Living Islam. It
attempts to demystify the religion (8.10).
</TEXT>
